node.text:
You, an intellectual: already knows the Greenland shark lives for centuries…. But HOW do they know that? 

This species has the nerve to be the hardest to age. With sharks, scientist can usually count the growth layers of cartilage that hardens over time, but the Greenland shark doesn't have any hard bits ("it's a very soft shark," according to scientist Julius Nielsen).

So scientists just decided to use a technique used on humans. 

Also, a correction (me: not an intellectual): In the video, I say “usually, you can tell how old a shark is by checking the rings in their earbones” but that doesn’t apply to sharks.

Source (actual intellectuals): 

Lynnerup N, Kjeldsen H, Heegaard S, Jacobsen C, Heinemeier J (2008) Radiocarbon Dating of the Human Eye Lens Crystallines Reveal Proteins without Carbon Turnover throughout Life. PLOS ONE 3(1): e1529. https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0001529

Nielsen J, Hedeholm R, Heinemeier J, Bushnell P, Christiansen J, Olsen J, Bronk Ramsey C, Brill R, Simon M, Steffensen K, Steffensen J. Eye lens radiocarbon reveals centuries of longevity in the Greenland shark (Somniosus microcephalus). Science. 2016; 353(6300):702-704.  DOI: 10.1126/science.aaf1703

node.text:
Coral reefs are often called the canary in the coal mine -- they’re extremely sensitive to slight changes in ocean conditions, and a leading indicator for how other ecosystems will respond to a changing climate. They’ve been around for 400 million years, but now they’re on track to disappear within a few decades. 

The corals in the Red Sea could hold the key to preserving other reefs, because they live in very warm, very salty water--conditions that mimic what the global ocean will look like in the coming decades. If we can figure out what mechanisms Red Sea corals use to thrive, scientists are hopeful we can take that knowledge and apply it to save coral reefs around the world.

From aboard the OceanXplorer during its maiden mission to the Red Sea, marine scientist Dr. Sam Purkis opens up about the frightening discoveries he makes studying the health of Red Sea coral reefs (including submarine dives up to 700 meters), and what they mean for the future of the ocean, and what he wants Gen-Z and future generations to know about what it will take to turn this around.

On its maiden mission to the Red Sea, #OceanXplorer made a surprising discovery: a brine pool, over 1700 meters below the surface, teeming with otherworldly life—extremophiles, to be precise, lifeforms that survive in conditions we wouldn't believe possible on our planet, and which provide clues to how life on Earth began. This is the first ever brine pool discovered in the Gulf of Aqaba, in the northern Red Sea.

node.text:
In 1962, John F Kennedy made a speech that launched what became known as the space race and committed the nation to the ambitious goal of landing on the Moon by the end of the decade. 
 
Almost 60 years later we have achieved thrilling feats of universal exploration that would surpass even Kennedy's wildest dreams, and at the same time we're beginning to understand the incredibly fragile and exquisite uniqueness of our own little planet. The UN declared 2021 the beginning of the Decade of Ocean Science, to emphasize the importance of understanding and protecting our (largely unexplored) planetary life-support system. And yet—fewer people probably know about that than they do about our recent forays to Mars or the FBI's upcoming declassification of sealed documents about UFOs. 

That's OK, but this #WorldOceansWeek, we want to remind people that there's also a whole "universe" out there waiting to be explored—and it's right here in our own oceans. The oceans are the source of life on Earth, and the answer to some of our greatest challenges. It's not rocket science. So follow us as we #ExploreWhatMatters.

node.title: Why ocean exploration matters more than space

Today is #WorldReefDay. #CoralReefs are critical for providing habitat and shelter and without them we wouldn't have much life in our #ocean at all.

And yet—almost 50 percent have disappeared since the 1970s. Our research in the #RedSea asks if the #corals here—which live in hyper warm and saline temperatures, just like corals of the future might face—can help us save them.

#ocean #eco #environment #savetheplanet #coralreef #extinctionisforever

node.title: How can we save the coral reefs?

node.text:
Not to alarm anyone but the #species known as the "#seagull" doesn't exist. That's just the colloquial term we apply to #birds, usually of the #gull family, of which there are more than 50 species, and all of them are very much land-based (compared to birds like, say, the #albatross, which spends years at a time without seeing land).

Although, to make it more confusing, they do belong to the group known as sea birds. 

Look, you can still call them seagulls, if you want to. In Japanese the term is "sea cats," because of the sound of their calls. 

@birdbrainuk in the #RedSea

node.title: Field Notes - Don’t Call Them Seagulls

node.text:
You, an intellectual: already knows the Greenland shark lives for centuries…. But HOW do they know that? 

This species has the nerve to be the hardest to age. With sharks, scientist can usually count the growth layers of cartilage that hardens over time, but the Greenland shark doesn't have any hard bits ("it's a very soft shark," according to scientist Julius Nielsen).

So scientists just decided to use a technique used on humans. 

Also, a correction (me: not an intellectual): In the video, I say “usually, you can tell how old a shark is by checking the rings in their earbones” but that doesn’t apply to sharks.

Source (actual intellectuals): 

Lynnerup N, Kjeldsen H, Heegaard S, Jacobsen C, Heinemeier J (2008) Radiocarbon Dating of the Human Eye Lens Crystallines Reveal Proteins without Carbon Turnover throughout Life. PLOS ONE 3(1): e1529. https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0001529

Nielsen J, Hedeholm R, Heinemeier J, Bushnell P, Christiansen J, Olsen J, Bronk Ramsey C, Brill R, Simon M, Steffensen K, Steffensen J. Eye lens radiocarbon reveals centuries of longevity in the Greenland shark (Somniosus microcephalus). Science. 2016; 353(6300):702-704.  DOI: 10.1126/science.aaf1703

Would you like to have a baby orca suck on your thumb? The volunteers taking care of Toa have this happen as they keep watch on the baby orca and make sure he doesn’t bump the sides of his pool. 

The 3-6 month old male #orca was stranded on rocks in Wellington, New Zealand a week ago. The search for his pod is still underway. They are currently investigating a pod sighting in Marlborough Sounds, but they have not been able to confirm yet if the #whales are Toa’s pod.

Due to the bad weather over the weekend, Toa is in a temporary pool. Tomorrow morning, it will be re-assessed if they can move the baby orca back to its sea pen. The calf is in stable condition and they are trying to minimize its stress, but they are conscious of the amount of time he’s been separated from his mother. 

#newzealand locals please keep a look out for orca pods off the lower North Island’s west coast or in Marlborough Sounds. If any are spotted, please provide as much information as possible to DOC, via marinemammals@doc.govt.nz or by calling 0800 DOC HOT. 

Essential information includes location of the pod, direction of travel of the animals, and photographs or videos which clearly show the saddle/back markings of the animals and their dorsal fins.

📸: @cattrin_

node.text:
#OceanNews: Photos from a recent paper (1) examining #shark bites on dolphins.*

Two dolphin species commonly seen around #Bimini, #Bahamas are the Atlantic spotted and the bottlenose dolphin. From hundreds of images, researchers found marks on 29% of the Atlantic spotted dolphins and 15% of the #bottlenose dolphins attributed to "attempted predation attempts," that is, #sharks trying to eat them. 

The reason this is important is because predator avoidance is a big factor in #dolphin behavior (for example, dolphins are observed with their calves more around Bimini during the shark off-season). The only marks counted as shark bites were "crescent-shaped injuries and deep, widely spaced tooth rakes" as well as "jagged injuries to the dorsal or pectoral fins" (to rule out any potential boat propeller or teeth-raking injuries). 

The researchers couldn't always tell what species left the bites, but these dolphins both overlap with bull and tiger sharks, which are known to prey on small cetaceans.

*Sometimes people get annoyed when we describe sharks doing what sharks do, as if they aren't apex predators. The part we want to stress is that sharks are discerning hunters that didn't evolve to eat and seek out YOU.

(1) Melillo‐Sweeting, K., Maust‐Mohl, M., & Smukall, M. J. (2021). Examining shark bite scars on dolphins off Bimini, The Bahamas: Comparisons between bottlenose and Atlantic spotted dolphins. Marine Mammal Science. Published. https://doi.org/10.1111/mms.12840

For more "cool shark stuff" check out @biminisharklab

#tigershark #bullshark #nature #natureismetal #science

“Gimme some fin”—the #turtles in “Finding Nemo” and #penguins in “Happy Feet” both say this to each other. And, to be fair, they are used interchangeably in general conversation. But in the case of penguins and turtles, it’s more accurate to say “flipper”: Flipper describes fleshy, broad, flattened limbs, whereas fins are finer, with no true bones, only cartilage. 

(And even though #shark fins look like the description of flippers, they are cartilage.)

In the Northern Red Sea, two ornithologists become some of the first to set foot on what look like tiny, barren-seeming desert islands—only to find that somebody is very much home. 

Travel with us as we explore the secret home of seabirds, including sooty falcons, incredible predators with a fascinating survival strategy—they time their nesting so that when their young hatch, it’s peak migration season for smaller birds—easy pickings for the falcons and their young. 

David Darrell-Lambert (@birdbrainuk) and Simon Parker (@parks1982) share their #knowledge as they conduct surveys of the wild bird life on these remote #islands in the #RedSea. 

Link is in our bio or bit.ly/red-sea-birds

Still images courtesy of David Darrell-Lambert, https://www.birdbrainuk.com.
